Predicators of Drug Overdose Deaths

Introduction

Where do most drug overdose deaths occur and what are some characteristics of those areas? Some of the socio-economic factors that were looked into were the median household income, high school completion rate, some college experience rate, and unemployment rate per state. Also some information about the most used drug in a drug overdose death.

Data

County Health Rankings: State, High School Completion, Some College Experience, Unemployment

Median Household Income: State, Household Income

12 Month-ending Provisional Number and Percent Change of Drug Overdose Deaths: State, Indicator, Data Value

Methods

K-Means Clustering

We implemented K-means clustering to determine if there were any correlation between a drug overdose death and the socio-economic factors listed. The reasons for using these four factors was because of their pre-existing relations to someone who uses drugs. People who are unemployed arent necessarily not working because they dont want. It can be very stressful looking for a job, and when people are stressed, they look for ways to relieve it and drugs is a common solution. In most communities, people who did not finish high school tend go down the route of drugs and potentially become an addict. Drugs of all kinds are present on college campuses and dents tend to indulge in taking drugs because there is immense peer pressure and no supervision. Household incomes and its relationship towards drug abuse can vary, especially based on the area.

Results

Since we grouped our data by states, we will look at which states share similarities and which of the factors do these states fall under.

There is wide spectrum of states that fall within the unemployment rate range. However, there is some correlation between unemployment rates and states with a lower drug overdose death. But the range is still too large for a concrete relationship.

Here we can see a common factor in where states share similarities among high school completion rate. States with a higher high school completion rate tend to have a lower number of drug overdose deaths. And most states with a high number of deaths lean towards the median of the HS completion rate.

Unlike the other two clusters, having some college experience seems to not have a clear or slightly visible effect on a drug overdose death.

Household income plays a little bit of a factor here as states with lower median household income tend to have a lower number of drug overdose deaths.

Discussion

Conclusions

Based on the results, we were able to conclude that some key factors that lead to most drug overdose deaths are:

High unemployment rate Low High school completion rate Low median household income

The only factor that did not have a clear effect was some college experience.

Limitations

Although given the county rankings data set that was very extensive, there was no variables involving drugs or drug overdose deaths. This lead to searching for external data, which no of had county level data. This is why the data was grouped by states instead of county.

Future Works

Some further research that can be done is obtaining data on a county level to broaden our EDA and clusters. Another topic that can be branched from this research is looking directly into the top five states and why they have such high drug overdose deaths. We discovered that opioids are the most used drug these cases. Looking more into what the opioid crisis looks like in each state can be an interesting project.
